Class MultiResolutionPath

  • All Implemented Interfaces:

    public class MultiResolutionPath
extends Path
    A Version of Path that provides level-of-detail. Positions in a Path are filtered based on a "skip count", the number of positions to skip between positions that are drawn. The skip-count algorithm can be replaced by the application. The default algorithm skips up to four positions, depending on the eye distance from the positions. Also, if the segment between any two positions is too small to be distinguished, it is not drawn. See makePositions(DrawContext, gov.nasa.worldwind.render.Path.PathData).

    • Constructor Detail

      • MultiResolutionPath

        public MultiResolutionPath(java.lang.Iterable<? extends Position> positions)
        Creates a path with specified positions. When the path is rendered, only path positions that are visually distinct for the current viewing state are considered. The path adjusts the positions it uses as the view state changes, using more of the specified positions as the eye point comes closer to the shape.

        Note: If fewer than two positions are specified, no path is drawn.

        Parameters:
        positions - the path positions. This reference is retained by this shape; the positions are not copied. If any positions in the set change, Path.setPositions(Iterable) must be called to inform this shape of the change.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if positions is null.

      • MultiResolutionPath

        public MultiResolutionPath(Position.PositionList positions)
        Creates a path with specified positions specified via a generic list. When the path is rendered, only path positions that are visually distinct for the current viewing state are considered. The path adjusts the positions it uses as the view state changes, using more of the specified positions as the eye point comes closer to the shape.

        Note: If fewer than two positions are specified, no path is drawn.

        Parameters:
        positions - the path positions. This reference is retained by this shape; the positions are not copied. If any positions in the set change, Path.setPositions(Iterable) must be called to inform this shape of the change.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if positions is null.
